The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary
                The governing council meeting of the Satyajit Ray Film and Television Institute will be held on April 24 in Mumbai. Chairman Buddhadeb Dasgupta informed students who had demanded the meeting about the changed date on Saturday evening. The meeting was earlier scheduled for April 10. Some of us can go to Mumbai. Well be given 20 minutes to present our case, said a student. Some students will go to Delhi around April 20 to meet the joint secretary of films. Classes are expected to resume at the institute after the governing council meeting.     An officer of North Port police station allegedly slapped the 29-year-old help of a Matador driver who refused him a bribe on Sunday afternoon. Santu Dutta, the help, filed a complaint stating that the officer stopped the vehicle on Strand Road and demanded money. Asit Pal, the deputy commissioner (port), said an investigation has been ordered into the incident.    A six-year-old girl died of burns on Sunday afternoon after a mini-generator burst in her house at Paltapara in Shyamnagar. Anouska Majumders clothes and a part of a room had caught fire after the explosion in the morning. The girl was taken to a nursing home where she died in the afternoon. Two fire tenders took 30 minutes to bring the blaze under control.     Subodhkant, 38, was arrested in Lalpur, Jharkhand, on Sunday afternoon for allegedly robbing two nationalised banks in Baguiati and Madhyamgram. Police recovered Rs 3,27,420 from his rented house. Another alleged member of the gang was held in Godda, Jharkhand, on Thursday.    The Election Commission on Saturday asked the CMC to not float tenders for cleaning the citys underground brick sewers till the elections. Chief electoral officer Debasish Sen allowed the civic body to continue with development and maintenance projects which started before elections were announced. According to a civic engineer, clearing the silt in sewers is necessary to prevent waterlogging during monsoon.    Jahangir Alam, 43, and Sunil Mondal, 45, were killed after the autorickshaw they were travelling in was hit by a small truck at Barasat on Sunday afternoon. Police said the autorickshaw was heading towards Barasat from Kadambagachi while the truck was moving in the opposite direction. Two other passengers were injured and had to be admitted to Barasat District Hospital.     A 26-year-old man hanged himself in his home in Salap, under Domjur police station, in Howrah, on Saturday night. Police said that Amol Pramanik was jobless and suffering from depression. No suicide note was found. The body was sent for post-mortem.     CPM and Trinamul activists clashed with each other near Siddeshwari Market, close to Birati railway overbridge, on Sunday afternoon over damage to a Mamata Banerjee banner. A police team and RAF brought the situation under control. A police picket has been posted in the area.            
